INSERT Articles ( Title, UrlSlug, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId, SiteId, Language ) VALUES ( N'Architectural Forum', N'architectural-forum', N'Architectural Forum was an influential American magazine that focused on the homebuilding industry and architecture. It had a long and notable history, with its roots dating back to 1892. The magazine began as The Brickbuilder, published in Boston, Massachusetts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'The Brickbuilder, initially a monthly publication, was founded in 1892. It focused on the promotion of high-quality brick architecture and provided information, inspiration, and resources to architects, builders, and homeowners. The magazine showcased innovative brick designs and featured articles on architectural trends, construction techniques, and notable projects.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'In October 1938, The Brickbuilder merged with another magazine called Architect''s World, resulting in the birth of Architectural Forum. This merger expanded the scope of the magazine, allowing it to cover a broader range of topics related to the architectural profession.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'Under its new name, Architectural Forum gained prominence as one of the leading publications in the field. It served as a platform for architects, designers, and industry professionals to share their ideas, innovations, and designs. The magazine played a significant role in shaping architectural discourse, promoting modernist principles, and documenting the changing landscape of American architecture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'Architectural Forum featured articles, essays, and editorials written by influential architects and critics, discussing architectural theory, design principles, urban planning, and social implications of the built environment. It showcased notable projects from around the world and provided readers with a comprehensive view of contemp